UP|44|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First, let's discuss the 2H bid. New suits by responder are forcing, whether or not there is an intervening overcall. Some people play new suits by responder to an overcall are not forcing. I don't like that approach  because it makes it very hard to bid many hands. I like to keep it simple. New suits by responder, whether pard is opener or overcaller, are forcing. |
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|What should Elizabeth bid? Certainly pass is one possibility. However, she likes her six card heart suit and stiff diamond. A negative double is a very reasonable bid. Then if Elizabeth later bids hearts, she is showing a long suit with a weak hand, a hand not good enough to bid 2H directly. So, if you make a negative double and then "correct" to your suit, that shows a hand too weak to bid your suit directly. That is exactly what Elizabeth has.|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT||NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. There were a couple of interesting issues there. At trick two, once Pam sees me lead a diamond, she should want to play trumps. Granted, if I have 7 spades, pard may have none. But it is more likely I have six spades and pard has one. Therefore, when I lead a diamond, she should play low and let Anna win the trick and play a spade. That way Pam does not have to lead away from her spade honors, but can still get spades lead. |
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Trick nine is the other issue. Anna should consider ruffing the Ace of diamonds with the J of spades. If you remember, Pam had Qx of spades at that point. Had Anna done that, then, I had to ruff with the King. And if I ruff with the King, then Pam's Q of spades ends up being good. That play is known as an "upper cut."|
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


AT|
lcmdir: How do I know that I should do that?|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You don't really, would have been easier if Pam led a lower diamond. But since your Jack of spades is not worth much, it might occur to you. The upper cut is a nice trump play that comes up on occasion. It is good to think about it when you are short in trump, but have a relatively high trump. I am not saying you should have seen it Anna, just pointing out it did exist on this hand. It is a good defensive technique to keep in mind.|
