^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|No, you have a clear 1C opener Anna. Particularly with strong minors, you have to have a really good hand to open 2C. Marty Bergen has his "4 and 4" rule for opening 2C when you have a major. |
PG| ***** 87 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The "4 and 4" means that you need 4+ quick tricks and four losers or less. Further, he does not use Losing Trick Count. He actually figures out how many losers he thinks he has. So, AK10xx is not a one loser suit, it is probably a 2.5 loser suit for example. But AKJ10x is a one loser suit. I use a slightly different rule.  I see if my hand can take nine tricks. |
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Sometimes it is not obvious, but with Anna's hand it is. She has an 8 trick hand, 7 clubs and a heart. If the Queen of hearts were the Ace of hearts instead, I might very well open 2C. Some people would also open Anna's hand a "gambling 3N." People do that with a solid minor suit and 8 sure tricks. My rule is I have to have eight top tricks. Anna has eight sure tricks, but only seven top tricks, so I would not personally open a gambling 3N. But if we change her KQ of hearts to the Ace of hearts, I would open it a gambling 3N. |
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Other people play gambling 3N shows an 8 card solid suit with no outside Aces or Kings. However, I think that is way too restrictive. Please note it is "gambling". Sometimes you might miss a slam, but the idea is the reward is worth the risk. That is the point of making these risky bids. If you are afraid to take risks, don't bid them.|
