^-{        Losing Trick Count - LTC         }
^-|HT|f|FP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|I am not a huge fan of Losing Trick Count (LTC), but it has its place. Let me discuss the mechanics first. Basically, every suit has up to three losers in it. So if you have three plus small, your suit has three losers. With an Ace, or King, or Queen, you eliminate a loser from that holding.|
PG| ***** 155 ***** |


fp|2|cs|4|AT|
^-
Three Plus Cards Suits
^-|FP||AT|^B@2^Y@3
Any three plus card suit have three losers unless it is headed headed by a Queen, a King, or an Ace. Such suit has only two losers. Suit holdings such as AQx, or KQx, or AKx has one loser.|
PG| ***** 156 ***** |


fp|2|cs|4|AT|

^-
Two-Card suits
^-|FP||AT|^B@2^Y@3
Two-card suits such as Qx or worse have two losers. There is only one loser in suits such as Ax or Kx.  Ax or Kx has one loser, and AK is no losers. |
PG| ***** 157 ***** |


fp|2|cs|4|AT|

^-
One-Card Suit
^-|FP||AT|^B@2^Y@3
A one card suit has one loser unless it is a singleton Ace. |
PG| ***** 158 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%LTC
qx||HT|e|cs|1|cp|4|
fp|1|3d|4|at|
^-{        Losing Trick Count - LTC         }
^-|HT|f|FP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Each hand can have a maximum of 12 losers (three losers in each suit). So, the combined partnership can have a maximum of 24 losers. Now, if you take the combined losers in both hands, and subtract from 24, that is how many tricks your side should be able to take. For example, if the partnership has seven losers for each hand, 24 - (7 x 2) = 10, the side could make four because making four is 10 tricks.|
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


AT|

That is the essence of losing trick count, take the combined losers between the two hands, subtract from 24 and that tells you how many tricks you can take. The question is, how do you figure out how many losers partner has. There are some rules of thumb.|
PG| ***** 160 ***** |


AT|

A minimum opening hand tends to be seven losers, a medium hand tends to have six losers and, a maximum hand tends to have five losers. A 2@C hand is usually a four losers or less. |
PG| ***** 161 ***** |


AT|

Similarly, minimum responder hand (6-9) has nine losers and a medium responder hand (10-12) has eight losers. |
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%
qx||HT|e|cs|1|cp|4|
fp|1|3d|4|at|
^-{        Losing Trick Count - LTC         }
^-|HT|f|FP||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Having said all that, I don't use LTC to figure out how high we should bid. I like LOTT much better. But here is where I sometimes use LTC. One very good use is to only when to open 2@C--if you have no more than a four-loser hand. Unless you have a balanced hand with 22 points or more, in which case you open 2@C and rebid 2N. Beside the borderline 2@C hands, LTC is a good guideline when I am deciding how good my hand is (for example, is it worth a reverse?). I might use LTC in that situation.|
PG| ***** 163 ***** |


AT|

So, I use LTC where I am not sure whether or not to open 2@C, I won't open unless I have four losers or less. When trying to decide whether to reverse, I need to have a six-loser hand, otherwise not a reverse. Similarly, when deciding whether or not to jump shift, (for example, 1C-1H-2S), I like to have a five-loser hand.|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


AT|

In summary, I rarely use LTC, just for those few hands where I am not sure how good my hand is.|
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


 
